<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,150,321]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,420,150,176]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Biology and notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[428,634,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eumerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigatus">
<emphasis box="[428,634,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Eumerus strigatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an exotic species considered a pest of onion and garlic crops. Later, the first record in 
<collectingCountry box="[360,421,186,212]" name="Chile" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Chile</collectingCountry>
was reported in 1978 by Vockeroth with samples reared by SAG (
<bibRefCitation author="Gerding, M. &amp; Cisternas, E. &amp; Aguilera, A. &amp; Apablaza, J." box="[1187,1424,186,213]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="133 - 135" refId="ref128846" refString="Gerding, M., Cisternas, E., Aguilera, A. &amp; Apablaza, J. (1999) Eumerus strigatus (Fallen) (Diptera: Syrphidae) infectando Alliaceae en Chile. Agricultura Tecnica, Chile, 9, 133 - 135." type="journal article" year="1999">
Gerding 
<emphasis box="[1290,1348,186,212]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al.</emphasis>
, 1999
</bibRefCitation>
). The larva penetrates the bulbs, turning the tissue into a pulpy texture. Adults are considered important pollinators of hyacinth, potatoes, carrots, and strawberries.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,150,321]" box="[199,1075,294,321]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,443,294,320]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Conservation status.</emphasis>
Not evaluated because this species is considered exotic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
